d"},"en":{"ABT 1369–1455":"about 1369–1455","1362–1429":"1362–1429","1365–Female":"1365–Deceased","1369–1455":"1369–1455","1373–Female":"1373–Deceased","1419–Male":"1419–Deceased","1342–1385":"1342–1385","1345–1393":"1345–1393","12 September 1385":"12 September 1385","1385":"1385","1373":"1373","1362":"1362","ABT 1369":"about 1369","1393":"1393","about 1419":"about 1419","1369":"1369","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1365":"1365","1342":"1342","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","Philleigh, Cornwall (England)":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall (England)":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Petit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Michel, Normand, Mireille, Philippe, Pierre, Achille, Armand, Jean Claude, Jean Jacques, Ketly, Adrien.","French, Walloon, Catalan, English, Jewish (from southern France), West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from (Old) French, Catalan, and Middle English <i>petit</i> ‘small’, hence a nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Pattee","meanings":["Altered form of French (Nord) <b>Pety</b>: variant of   Petit  . This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Petion","meanings":["French and Haitian (<b>Pétion</b>): diminutive of   Petit  . This surname was brought to the US from Haiti, where it is by far most common."]},{"name":"Petite","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celestine, Jacques.","French: from the feminine form of   Petit   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Petitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettett","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Little","meanings":["English: nickname for a small man (if not ironic), or distinguishing epithet for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, from Middle English <i>littel</i>, Old English <i>lȳtel</i> (see   Light   3).","Irish: translation into English of Gaelic <b>Ó Beagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beagán</i>’ (see   Began  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of any of various European surnames meaning ‘little’, e.g. French   Petit  , Polish <b>Mały</b> (see   Maly   1)."]},{"name":"Petee","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettit","meanings":["English (mainly southeastern): variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Petito","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Pasquale, Antonio, Rocco, Alfonzo, Alphonso, Antimo, Emilio, Giovanni, Giuseppe, Orazio, Salvatore, Silvio, Tullio, Virginio.","Italian: nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a tall one), from dialect <i>petito</i> ‘small’ or from the personal name <i>Petito</i>; compare French   Petit  ."]}]},{"name":"Michael","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a common biblical name (meaning ‘who is like God?’ in Hebrew) borne by one of the archangels, the protector of the ancient Hebrews, who is also regarded as a saint of the Catholic Church. In the Middle Ages, Michael was regarded as captain of the heavenly host (see Revelation 12:7–9), symbol of the Church Militant, and patron of soldiers. He was often depicted bearing a flaming sword. The name is also borne by a Persian prince and ally of Belshazzar mentioned in the Book of Daniel. Since the early 1900s it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names in the English-speaking world.  See also  Michal ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Michael Petit II was born about 1369, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, his father, Michael Le Petit, was 28 and his mother, Amicia Bloyou, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Michael Petit II. He died in 1455, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 87."},"et":{"ABT 1369–1455":"umbes 1369–1455","1362–1429":"1362–1429","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1369–1455":"1369–1455","1373–Female":"1373–Surnud","1419–Male":"1419–Surnud","1342–1385":"1342–1385","1345–1393":"1345–1393","12 September 1385":"12. september 1385","1385":"1385","1373":"1373","1362":"1362","ABT 1369":"umbes 1369","1393":"1393","about 1419":"umbes 1419","1369":"1369","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1365":"1365","1342":"1342","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","Philleigh, Cornwall (England)":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall (England)":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"ABT 1369–1455":"noin 1369–1455","1362–1429":"1362–1429","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1369–1455":"1369–1455","1373–Female":"1373–Kuollut","1419–Male":"1419–Kuollut","1342–1385":"1342–1385","1345–1393":"